  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The New York AM session (08:30–11:00 EST), centered on the 9:30 NYSE open, representing the distribution phase of the AMD cycle. It typically features an initial manipulation sweep at 08:30 or 09:30, followed by a change in state of delivery, expanding price toward higher-timeframe liquidity draws such as previous day high/low or session extremes. Behavior varies by daily profile: in Seek and Destroy, NY consolidates; in London Reversal and New York Reversal profiles, NY is the primary execution window.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Mark the New York AM session window from 08:30 to 11:00 EST, with the 9:30 candle as a key timestamp.",
    "Identify 08:30 as the first key sub-level where a manipulation (opposing) price run is expected, often forming a new order block.",
    "Identify 09:30 as the second key sub-level where a continuation move in the true directional bias is expected, often sweeping highs or lows established at 08:30.",
    "Mark 10:00 EST (4-hour open) as an additional time level within the session where continuation or reversal moves may complete.",
    "Determine the applicable daily profile before interpreting NY price action: (a) Seek and Destroy — London swept both sides of the Asia Range without sustained expansion, NY consolidates; (b) London Reversal — London confirmed a Change in State of Delivery between 02:00–05:00 EST, NY continues in that direction; (c) New York Reversal — London failed to reach a relevant higher time frame PD Array and did not form the session's significant high or low, NY produces the reversal.",
    "In Seek and Destroy conditions, observe whether price exits an established range (Asia or London range) and returns back inside rather than displacing and holding outside; mark equilibrium (0.5 level) of the range as the NY price magnet.",
    "In London Reversal or New York Reversal profiles, look for a Change in the State of Delivery (close beyond a series of same-direction candles) at or near the 08:30 or 09:30 time levels to confirm the setup.",
    "The order block or propulsion block formed by the 08:30 manipulation run becomes a valid entry reference once price closes back through it in the true directional bias.",
    "Assess whether London has already created most of the daily range before NY opens; if so, classify NY as low-probability for directional trades (Seek and Destroy conditions).",
    "Note overlapping confluences such as the Midnight Open aligning with the 08:30 level to increase trade quality.",
    "Confirm Asia accumulation/London manipulation (or consolidation) occurred prior to the New York open; if key liquidity targets (e.g., previous day high/low) have already been swept, skip the session.",
    "Look for an initial manipulation move (sweep of a prior high/low, opposing range, or news spike) at or shortly after the 08:30 or 9:30 open.",
    "Wait for a Change in State of Delivery (CISD) on a lower timeframe (e.g., 5-minute) where price closes through the series of opposing candles that produced the manipulation.",
    "Enter on a retest of the order block or fair value gap formed following the CISD, using the 9:30 open as support/resistance confluence.",
    "Target higher-timeframe draw on liquidity: previous day high/low, opposing session extremes, or standard deviation projections (e.g., -2 to -2.5) from the London manipulation leg.",
    "Confirm entries with lower timeframe displacement or SMT divergence at key levels within the New York window."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "In London Reversal and New York Reversal profiles, the New York Open is the primary execution window: wait for the 08:30 manipulation sweep to form an order block, enter on a Change in State of Delivery close, and target resting liquidity (failure swings, session highs/lows, previous day high/low) with a minimum 2R reward. In Seek and Destroy profiles, NY offers low-probability directional setups; trade from outside the range back toward equilibrium and the opposing range extreme rather than attempting breakouts. Entries are taken on lower timeframe order blocks or fair value gaps, with stops beyond the manipulation extreme.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Attempting to trade breakouts or directional expansions out of the range during NY when London has already swept both sides of the Asia Range, leading to failed breakout trades.",
    "Expecting NY to produce a large move when London has already created most of the daily range, resulting in overtrading low-probability conditions.",
    "Trading from inside the range outward (inside-out) rather than from outside the range back inward (outside-in) during Seek and Destroy conditions.",
    "Treating a London move that sweeps lows and reverses as a London Reversal without verifying that a relevant higher time frame PD Array was actually reached; if no HTF level was engaged, the setup is a New York Reversal.",
    "Entering on the first apparent Change in the State of Delivery during London or early New York without confirming it is not a fake reversal designed to run liquidity again before the true move.",
    "Ignoring the 08:30 and 09:30 time levels and missing the specific manipulation and continuation structure that defines the New York Open within the daily profile.",
    "Entering in the continuation direction immediately at 08:30 without waiting for a manipulation sweep to form an order block, missing a higher-probability entry.",
    "Ignoring the 08:30 manipulation move as noise rather than recognizing it as a setup trigger for the true continuation direction.",
    "Failing to use 09:30 and 10:00 as secondary time-level checkpoints, causing premature exits or missed continuation entries.",
    "Trading the New York Open without first confirming a Change in State of Delivery during London (02:00–05:00), leading to entries without a valid daily profile bias.",
    "Entering on the initial manipulation sweep without waiting for a Change in State of Delivery (CISD) or displacement confirmation.",
    "Trading the London reversal directly instead of waiting for the New York 9:30 continuation.",
    "Misinterpreting the 9:30 initial move as the true directional move without recognizing it can be a Judas swing that soon reverses.",
    "Ignoring the confluence of the 9:30 open with midnight open and 8:30 open when assessing support/resistance.",
    "Applying the 9:30 open rules to Forex markets, where the NYSE open is not a relevant driver.",
    "Looking for entries outside of premium/discount within the dealing range rather than within the correct half.",
    "Taking trades below a minimum 2R when projecting the manipulation leg to standard deviation targets would provide a valid target.",
    "Trading the New York session when previous day high or low has already been swept during Asia or London, leaving no clean draw on liquidity.",
    "Assuming a valid entry setup must be available every trading day.",
    "Using the order block opening price instead of the mean threshold/discount when a deeper retracement is more appropriate to the range.",
    "Expecting New York continuation when London already reached the higher timeframe key level, removing the draw on liquidity.",
    "Treating the first low/high reached after 9:30 as the higher timeframe target rather than an intermediate level on the way to the actual draw.",
    "Misreading a single candle direction (e.g., up-close candle in a bearish bias) without waiting for structural confirmation (close below opposing series)."
  ],
